From 49bf2811508128f377fe421fcd17dd49a038045a Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Dong Chenchen <superdcc97@163.com>
Date: Sat, 25 Apr 2026 15:49:56 +0800
Subject: [PATCH 3/4] mm: shard i_mmap interval tree with per-shard locks

The per-mapping i_mmap_rwsem is a central contention point on high-core
machines running execve-intensive workloads. Replace it with a sharded
design:

- Add I_MMAP_NR_SHARDS (4) per-mapping interval trees, each with its
  own rwsem. Lazy allocation on first VMA insertion means non-mmap'd
  inodes have zero overhead.
- Add a Kconfig option CONFIG_MM_IMMAP_SHARD (default n).
- VMA shard index derived from vm_pgoff hash, NOT NUMA-based, so
  single-node-high-core systems benefit equally.
- Locking protocol when sharded:
  - i_mmap_lock_write(): top-level read lock (shared for ops)
  - i_mmap_shard_lock_write(): per-shard write lock
  - i_mmap_lock_read(): top-level write lock (exclusive for traversal)
- vma_interval_tree_foreach_sharded() macro transparently iterates all
  shards (or single tree when non-sharded).
- When CONFIG_MM_IMMAP_SHARD=n, all code compiles to the original
  behavior with zero overhead.

This addresses community feedback on Huang Shijie's NUMA-based split:
no per-inode memory bloat, no NUMA dependency, no type-confusing
foreach macro, no hardcoded GFP_KERNEL in allocation paths.
